1. Interference

Interference is a known phenomenon in classical physics. If multiple waves are superimposed, they interfere and form patterns of destructive and constructive interference. This behavior can be easily observed in e.g. water waves. Click somewhere on the left side and see what interesting patterns you can create.

2. The Double-Slit

The double-slit is one of the most iconic experiments in physics and was first performed with light in 1801 by Thomas Young. It consisted of a source of light, two slits and a screen on which the interference could be observed. The interference fringes confirmed that light was a wave.

3. Matter-Waves

That light is just a wave was contested by Albert Einstein in his explanation for the photoelectric effect, which asserted that light can act as a particle. This discovery earned him the Nobel prize of 1921. In Louis de Broglie's famous doctoral thesis from 1924 he proposed the idea that matter might exibit wave-behavior. His revolutionary idea was confirmed one year later in experiments using electrons to generate interference fringes with a double-slit.

4. Quantum Mechanics

Inspired by de Broglie's hypothesis that matter could be described as a wave, Erwin Schrdinger published a wave-equation which was able to describe the physical structure of the hydrogen atom (ecerpt from original publication): This equation is nowaday known as the Schrdinger equation and the very cornerstone of quantum mechanics.
